-Enable Virtual Functions (VFs) on Intel Arc Pro-

Must use Proxmox 9.1.4 or higher, with Kernel 6.17.13 or higher.

Ensure IOMMU / SR-IOV is enabled in Proxmox.

Locate your Intel Arc Pro card on the PCIe Bus

lspci | grep G31

    \\ 83:00.0 Intel Battlemage G31 [Intel Graphics] \\

I ran into an flr reset issue on my configuration, so this was my workaround once I had the address for my B70

Create service to split the gpu into N VFs on startup (optional)

nano /etc/systemd/system/bifurcate.service
[Unit]
Description=Split B70 into two VFs
After=network-online.target pve-cluster.service
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=oneshot
RemainAfterExit=yes
ExecStart=/bin/sh /usr/local/bin/bifurcate.sh

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Save file and close

nano /usr/local/bin/bifurcate.sh

!#/bin/bash

echo 2 > /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000\:83\:00.0/sriov_numvfs

Save file and close

Start the service

systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl enable bifurcate.service
systemctl start bifurcate.service

If you did not do the above, use the following command to bifurcate the GPU, where <num_vfs> = 1-4

echo <num_vfs> > /sys/bus/pci/devices/<pci_device_path>/sriov_numvfs

Example: echo 4 > /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000\:03\:00.0/sriov_numvfs

0000:83:00.1
0000:83:00.2
0000:83:00.3
0000:83:00.4

0000:83:00.0 is the physical GPU, and should not be passed through to a VM, or the sub-devices will fail.

At this point I hit an FLR reset issue on my B70, where passing the VF into a virtual machine caused all VFs to be disabled due to (I think) the Xe driver trying to grab control of the VF during reset. We don't want this, so we disable the VF, then manually enable it with the vfio-pci driver

We create a hookscript to run at startup for our vms:

nano /var/lib/vz/snippets/arc-vf-fix.sh
(The below script is overkill and is mostly from a debug session with gemini. It can probably be sinplified but I find it cool af)

#!/bin/bash
VMID=$1
PHASE=$2

if [ "$PHASE" == "pre-start" ]; then
    echo "=== Arc B70 SR-IOV Initialization for VM $VMID ==="
    
    # 1. Grab raw PCI assignment lines from the VM config file
    RAW_CONF=$(qm config $VMID | grep -E "hostpci[0-9]")
    echo "Raw Proxmox Config Line: $RAW_CONF"

    # 2. Try to extract direct hardware IDs (e.g., 83:00.2)
    VF_ADDRESS=$(echo "$RAW_CONF" | grep -o '83:00\.[0-9]')

    # 3. Fallback: If you used Proxmox GUI "Resource Mapping", look for mapped indexes
    if [ -z "$VF_ADDRESS" ]; then
        # Extracts mapped lines if Proxmox formatted it like "mapping=ArcGPU,index=2"
        MAPPED_INDEX=$(echo "$RAW_CONF" | grep -o 'index=[0-9]' | cut -d'=' -f2)
        if [ ! -z "$MAPPED_INDEX" ]; then
            # Convert 0-indexed mappings to standard hardware addresses (.1, .2, etc)
            # Typically index=0 is 83:00.1, index=1 is 83:00.2, etc. Adjust if necessary.
            VF_NUM=$((MAPPED_INDEX + 1))
            VF_ADDRESS="83:00.$VF_NUM"
        fi
    fi

    # 4. Critical Halt if no hardware can be parsed
    if [ -z "$VF_ADDRESS" ]; then
        echo "ERROR: Could not parse Arc Virtual Function address from configuration!"
        echo "Please verify VM $VMID has an Arc device assigned in the GUI."
        exit 1
    fi

    FULL_PCI="0000:$VF_ADDRESS"
    echo "Targeting Hardware Address: $FULL_PCI"

    # 5. Sever the active host graphics module control
    if [ -e "/sys/bus/pci/devices/$FULL_PCI/driver/unbind" ]; then
        echo "Unbinding $FULL_PCI from host 'xe' driver..."
        echo "$FULL_PCI" > "/sys/bus/pci/devices/$FULL_PCI/driver/unbind" 2>/dev/null
    else
        echo "$FULL_PCI already unbound or isolated."
    fi

    # 6. Bind to the VFIO ecosystem (Forces /dev/vfio/9x to spawn). replace e223 with your device string
    echo "8086 e223" > /sys/bus/pci/drivers/vfio-pci/new_id 2>/dev/null || true
    echo "$FULL_PCI" > /sys/bus/pci/drivers/vfio-pci/bind 2>/dev/null
    
    echo "=== Sync Complete. Virtualization Node Spawned ==="
fi

Attach the script as a hookscript to our vm

qm set 101 --hookscript local:snippets/arc-vf-fix.sh

Add the VF to our vm via the config file args

nano /etc/pve/qemu-server/101.conf
args: -device vfio-pci,host=83:00.2,id=hostpci0,x-vga=on

This should work for anywhere from 1-7 VFs if you see an flr reset error or you see your VFs disappear when trying to pass one into your vm.

--NOTE--

If passing through to a Windows 11 VM, you MUST select [HOST] as the virtual CPU type. Emulated CPU modes like the default [x86-64-v2-AES] will result in the driver failing to load, with a CODE 43 error.
